USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, which he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the same text used several times as "just like in Iraq," but it also failed to use the title of the January 2007 Bush statement for his own statement, "A New Road Forward."
It was himself, who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country suffering from civil war. And that criticized it as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today there is nothing talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, however objectively left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even in spite of traditional subordinate relationships, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40, 000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so he at least deceived the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing about Obama's entire strategy seems like his goal, start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months, and completing this procedure in three years. Obama's entire doctrine generated more questions than the answers he offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, while formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin. Patriarchal tribal relations will remain behind him.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum target of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy clashes with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "return home soon," will perform some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of troop withdrawal is pure irresponsible, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect statement of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the U.S. will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
Answers will need to be sought precisely when, according to Obama, America initiates the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each solution like this will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential election is three years away, and that's why there's still plenty of time to find another strategy, if it's a total failure.
