A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'silenced' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some drugs already accessible.
AIDS disease can't be cured until now.
However, patients' lives can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If virus replication is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of the experts of three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, V-CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way from all drugs used today, which is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, 'enhanced' compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyedr cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are bound by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resilient virus
HIV proteasis is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV proteasis, HIV virus fractionation does not occur and no mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV proteasis, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry scientists describe a number of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still systematically modified.
