The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging stances and mutual recriminations, drew renewed attention on Friday with the dissemination of a document that envisages ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a time-running negotiation, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Drawn up by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give to the poor to cope with short- and long-term global warming.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global temperature rise that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized an 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their own over the same period by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the conversations last week.
U.S. Special Climate Envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, compared to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States is not going to make an agreement without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei claimed that America's top climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for having said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically cope with global overheating.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the bravest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that major powers are discussing who should afford the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, argued Ulate, who also works as regional climate change advisor for Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, even if most major participants say that the talks will produce at most political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States developed a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most exceptional issues before heads of government come to close a deal.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran down the corridors of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, so they could delimit the claims to be arbitrated over the next week.
