Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our fight for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees sticking to "values" determined from above as it was before it was about imposing products designed by factory technicians on consumers.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquering the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Employee demobilization can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&amp;D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behavior and a forward-looking vision." it needs a commitment on the part of employees that completely opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would be to put employees at the center of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls are of relative use
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
-Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behavioral theory that American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and which the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commandos" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management stance, unacpathed to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motifuncional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a pre-determined doxa that allows them, through their image of the company, to evaluate what the company offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilization factors, company managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate the management of human resources "on site".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
