The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long, 1.50-meter-tall animal running on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Journal of Science.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis team member of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered in total the remains of five specimens.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not quite share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
So the experts are discussing, for example, on when saurios were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: carnivorous theropods including Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and birds, quadrupedal sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and Hervorous Ornithischiabi (saurios with bird pelvis), to which they belong, , the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, nesbitt says.
For example, in Tawa's skull found evidence of air pockets, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to airbags, bird breathing is more efficient than mammals.
In Tawa's case he also found the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed airbags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs previously known lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurios first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were originally separated and spread from South America throughout all corners of the Earth, which at the time still formed a unique land mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa to find the remains of two other not closely related theropods.
All three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurios.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct on the triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to defeat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact brakes the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and had since led to a miserable existence: mammals.
