He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on multi-day journeys following an operation of heart valves with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he was prostrate in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watched over his health.
It was seen in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorbike kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with firn snow and met a Korean mobster.
He gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so it describes your experience.
On the contrary, memories of mental travel are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience will dilute the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and narcotics consumption show how fragile the inner reproduction of outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Each modification of the state of consciousness, the psychologist Kasten sums up, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
