75% of working mothers have had work problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fertility and work history of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women between the age of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study notes that there are many differences in the onset of couples and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an uns stable job, start partner coexistence first, advance first motherhood, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have less offspring.
"Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time than their life trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work done has a lot of influence on motherhood but less on the schedule of pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that differentiates women's age by getting married and having the first stem.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the age at which they marry and at which they have the first child.
The difference also remains between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
"Another division is also established among women according to their level of study.
While those with elementary studies marry and have their first child before achieving a stable job, those of medium or higher levels reverse this sequence and prioritize obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado says.
