Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As with ABS brake anti-locking and will go through ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they already are in all new enrolment passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a gap period is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian protection although, by the way it works, it can also help prevent many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the trampl given by the driver.
But this one doesn't always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brakes before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four claims with harm to people would be avoided - when so-called the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via radar or camera) detects obstacles and alerts the driver, in addition to acting lightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
